nula","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100.–1159","1080–Female":"1080–preminula","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"oko 1080.","1100":"1100.","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"cs":{"about 1080–":"okolo 1080–Zesnulá","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Zesnulá","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"okolo 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"about 1080–":"omkring 1080–Afdød","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Afdød","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"omkring 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1080–":"circa 1080–Overleden","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Overleden","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"circa 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"about 1080–":"about 1080–Deceased","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"about 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lindsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Linzy","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish, Irish, or English   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  . Compare   Lenzy  ."]},{"name":"Linzey","meanings":["English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  ."]},{"name":"Lindsey","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Lincoln","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."]},{"name":"Linsey","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, or English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  .","Americanized form of German   Linse   or Swiss German <b>Linsi</b>, see   Lins  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Lindsay was born about 1080, in Scotland. She had at least 1 son with Gilbert De  Colville."},"et":{"about 1080–":"umbes 1080–Surnud","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1080–":"noin 1080–Kuollut","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"noin 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1080–":"environ 1080–Décédée","1066–1130":"1066–1130","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","about 1080":"environ 1080","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1130":"1130","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Margaret Lindsay est née environ 1080, à Écosse. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Gilbert De  Colville."